&gt;&gt; Andrew McDonagh wrote:
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; I use the following pattern...
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; public void testVariousParams() {
&gt;&gt;&gt;       paramTest(&quot;a param&quot;;
&gt;&gt;&gt;       paramTest(&quot;second test param&quot;);
&gt;&gt;&gt;       ....
&gt;&gt;&gt; }
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; private void paramTest(String expectedValue) {
&gt;&gt;&gt;       Something something = new Something();
&gt;&gt;&gt;       assertEquals(&quot;didn&#39;t work&quot;, expectedvalue,
&gt;&gt;&gt; something.getValue()); }
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; The only issue is that the private test case methods cannot be named
&gt;&gt;&gt; test**** as the JUnit framework moans about them being private or
&gt;&gt;&gt; having params.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Extract testVariousParams() into the suite() method and you have the
&gt;&gt; beginnings of the Parameterized Test Case pattern. The above is
&gt;&gt; exactly how I used to do it. --
